#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:4
msgid "read - read line of input into variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:7
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr "概要"

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:9
msgid "read [OPTIONS] [VARIABLE ...]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:14
msgid "Description"
msgstr "描述"

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:16
msgid ""
"``read`` reads from standard input and either writes the result back to "
"standard output (for use in command substitution), or stores the result in "
"one or more shell variables. By default, ``read`` reads a single line and "
"splits it into variables on spaces or tabs. Alternatively, a null character "
"or a maximum number of characters can be used to terminate the input, and "
"other delimiters can be given. Unlike other shells, there is no default "
"variable (such as :envvar:`REPLY`) for storing the result - instead, it is "
"printed on standard output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:18
msgid "The following options are available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:20
msgid "**-c** *CMD* or **--command** *CMD*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:21
msgid ""
"Sets the initial string in the interactive mode command buffer to *CMD*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:23
msgid "**-d** or **--delimiter** *DELIMITER*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:24
msgid ""
"Splits on *DELIMITER*. *DELIMITER* will be used as an entire string to split "
"on, not a set of characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:26
msgid "**-g** or **--global**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:27
msgid "Makes the variables global."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:29
msgid "**-s** or **--silent**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:30
msgid ""
"Masks characters written to the terminal, replacing them with asterisks. "
"This is useful for reading things like passwords or other sensitive "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:32
msgid "**-f** or **--function**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:33
msgid ""
"Scopes the variable to the currently executing function. It is erased when "
"the function ends."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:35
msgid "**-l** or **--local**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:36
msgid ""
"Scopes the variable to the currently executing block. It is erased when the "
"block ends. Outside of a block, this is the same as **--function**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:38
msgid "**-n** or **--nchars** *NCHARS*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:39
msgid ""
"Makes ``read`` return after reading *NCHARS* characters or the end of the "
"line, whichever comes first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:41
msgid "**-p** or **--prompt** *PROMPT_CMD*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:42
msgid ""
"Uses the output of the shell command *PROMPT_CMD* as the prompt for the "
"interactive mode. The default prompt command is ``set_color green; echo "
"read; set_color normal; echo \"> \"``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:44
msgid "**-P** or **--prompt-str** *PROMPT_STR*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:45
msgid ""
"Uses the *PROMPT_STR* as the prompt for the interactive mode. It is "
"equivalent to ``echo $PROMPT_STR`` and is provided solely to avoid the need "
"to frame the prompt as a command. All special characters in the string are "
"automatically escaped before being passed to the :doc:`echo <echo>` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:47
msgid "**-R** or **--right-prompt** *RIGHT_PROMPT_CMD*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:48
msgid ""
"Uses the output of the shell command *RIGHT_PROMPT_CMD* as the right prompt "
"for the interactive mode. There is no default right prompt command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:50
msgid "**-S** or **--shell**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:51
msgid ""
"Enables syntax highlighting, tab completions and command termination "
"suitable for entering shellscript code in the interactive mode. NOTE: Prior "
"to fish 3.0, the short opt for **--shell** was **-s**, but it has been "
"changed for compatibility with bash's **-s** short opt for **--silent**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:53
msgid "**-t** -or **--tokenize**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:54
msgid ""
"Causes read to split the input into variables by the shell's tokenization "
"rules. This means it will honor quotes and escaping. This option is of "
"course incompatible with other options to control splitting like **--"
"delimiter** and does not honor :envvar:`IFS` (like fish's tokenizer). It "
"saves the tokens in the manner they'd be passed to commands on the "
"commandline, so e.g. ``a\\ b`` is stored as ``a b``. Note that currently it "
"leaves command substitutions intact along with the parentheses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:56
msgid "**-u** or **--unexport**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:57
msgid ""
"Prevents the variables from being exported to child processes (default "
"behaviour)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:59
msgid "**-U** or **--universal**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:60
msgid "Causes the specified shell variable to be made universal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:62
msgid "**-x** or **--export**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:63
msgid "Exports the variables to child processes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:65
msgid "**-a** or **--list**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:66
msgid ""
"Stores the result as a list in a single variable. This option is also "
"available as **--array** for backwards compatibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:68
msgid "**-z** or **--null**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:69
msgid ""
"Marks the end of the line with the NUL character, instead of newline. This "
"also disables interactive mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:71
msgid "**-L** or **--line**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:72
msgid ""
"Reads each line into successive variables, and stops after each variable has "
"been filled. This cannot be combined with the ``--delimiter`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:74
msgid ""
"Without the ``--line`` option, ``read`` reads a single line of input from "
"standard input, breaks it into tokens, and then assigns one token to each "
"variable specified in *VARIABLES*. If there are more tokens than variables, "
"the complete remainder is assigned to the last variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:76
msgid ""
"If no option to determine how to split like ``--delimiter``, ``--line`` or "
"``--tokenize`` is given, the variable ``IFS`` is used as a list of "
"characters to split on. Relying on the use of ``IFS`` is deprecated and this "
"behaviour will be removed in future versions. The default value of ``IFS`` "
"contains space, tab and newline characters. As a special case, if ``IFS`` is "
"set to the empty string, each character of the input is considered a "
"separate token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:78
msgid ""
"With the ``--line`` option, ``read`` reads a line of input from standard "
"input into each provided variable, stopping when each variable has been "
"filled. The line is not tokenized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:80
msgid ""
"If no variable names are provided, ``read`` enters a special case that "
"simply provides redirection from standard input to standard output, useful "
"for command substitution. For instance, the fish shell command below can be "
"used to read data that should be provided via a command line argument from "
"the console instead of hardcoding it in the command itself, allowing the "
"command to both be reused as-is in various contexts with different input "
"values and preventing possibly sensitive text from being included in the "
"shell history::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:82
msgid "mysql -uuser -p(read)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:84
msgid ""
"When running in this mode, ``read`` does not split the input in any way and "
"text is redirected to standard output without any further processing or "
"manipulation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:86
msgid ""
"If ``-a`` or ``--array`` is provided, only one variable name is allowed and "
"the tokens are stored as a list in this variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:88
msgid ""
"See the documentation for ``set`` for more details on the scoping rules for "
"variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:90
msgid ""
"When ``read`` reaches the end-of-file (EOF) instead of the terminator, the "
"exit status is set to 1. Otherwise, it is set to 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:93
msgid ""
"In order to protect the shell from consuming too many system resources, "
"``read`` will only consume a maximum of 100 MiB (104857600 bytes); if the "
"terminator is not reached before this limit then *VARIABLE* is set to empty "
"and the exit status is set to 122. This limit can be altered with the :"
"envvar:`fish_read_limit` variable. If set to 0 (zero), the limit is removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:99
msgid "Example"
msgstr "範例"

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:101
msgid "``read`` has a few separate uses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:103
msgid ""
"The following code stores the value 'hello' in the shell variable :envvar:"
"`foo`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:107
msgid "echo hello|read foo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:109
msgid ""
"The :doc:`while <while>` command is a neat way to handle command output line-"
"by-line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:111
msgid ""
"printf '%s\\n' line1 line2 line3 line4 | while read -l foo\n"
"                  echo \"This is another line: $foo\"\n"
"              end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:115
msgid "Delimiters given via \"-d\" are taken as one string::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:117
msgid ""
"echo a==b==c | read -d == -l a b c\n"
"echo $a # a\n"
"echo $b # b\n"
"echo $c # c"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:122
msgid ""
"``--tokenize`` honors quotes and escaping like the shell's argument passing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:124
msgid ""
"echo 'a\\ b' | read -t first second\n"
"echo $first # outputs \"a b\", $second is empty\n"
"\n"
"echo 'a\"foo bar\"b (command echo wurst)*\" \"{a,b}' | read -lt -l a b c\n"
"echo $a # outputs 'afoo barb' (without the quotes)\n"
"echo $b # outputs '(command echo wurst)* {a,b}' (without the quotes)\n"
"echo $c # nothing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/read.rst:132
msgid ""
"For an example on interactive use, see :ref:`Querying for user input <user-"
"input>`."
msgstr ""
